<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Finding 3 · IDOR</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <div class="brand brand-sm" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">🔢</div>
      <h1>Finding 3 confirmed</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Day 3 · Insecure Direct Object Reference</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📚</div>
        <h2>The vulnerability</h2>
        <h3>Authentication ≠ Authorization</h3>
        <p>The endpoint asked "are you logged in?" but never asked "should you see <em>this</em> object?". Sequential IDs (or any guessable identifier) plus a missing per-object authz check equals access to every record in the database.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📰</div>
        <h2>Seen in the wild</h2>
        <h3>OWASP API #1</h3>
        <p>Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA / IDOR) tops the OWASP API Security list. Facebook, T-Mobile, USPS, Parler, and dozens of fintech apps have leaked customer records via this exact bug. Usually one HTTP request from "your account" to "someone else's account."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🛠️</div>
        <h2>How to fix it</h2>
        <h3>Authorize per object, per request</h3>
        <p>On every fetch of a customer-scoped resource, verify the requesting user actually owns it (or has staff role). Don't rely on the ID being unguessable. Use UUIDs <em>and</em> server-side checks. Defense in depth.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>One-line takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Every ID is attacker-controlled</h3>
        <p>If the URL contains an identifier, assume the attacker will try every value. Build the authz check into the data access layer so it's impossible to forget at the route handler.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All findings</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %><a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Day <%= nextNum %> →</a><% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
